\fs28 \cf2 SSH, or\'a0
\f2\b S
\f0\b0 ecure\'a0
\f2\b Sh
\f0\b0 ell, provides a secure channel to access other computers. We commonly use SSH to remotely log in and connect securely to other servers. To practice with SSH we will be setting up our own remote servers using Amazon EC2. This setup can be a bit intimidating, but it's a very valuable skill to know with any kind of development. Let's get started!\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl520\sa200

\fs48 \cf2 Setting up an EC2 Instance\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf2 As evidenced by the list below, there are a fair number of steps involved in setting up your instance. The links provided also provide a fair amount of context, and help explain the purpose of each of the following steps.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200
\ls4\ilvl0\cf2 {\listtext	1.	}Make sure that you have an Amazon Web Services (AWS) account. You can log in / sign up\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docs.aws.amazon.com/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 here}}\'a0and click on the top right.\
{\listtext	2.	}Create an IAM user\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/get-set-up-for-amazon-ec2.html#create-an-iam-user"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 here}}.\
{\listtext	3.	}Create a key pair\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/get-set-up-for-amazon-ec2.html#create-a-key-pair"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 here}}\
{\listtext	4.	}Create a VPC\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/get-set-up-for-amazon-ec2.html#create-a-vpc"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 here}}\
{\listtext	5.	}Create a Security Group\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/get-set-up-for-amazon-ec2.html#create-a-base-security-group"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 here}}\
{\listtext	6.	}Launch your instance\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/EC2_GetStarted.html#ec2-launch-instance_linux"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 here}}\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa400
\ls4\ilvl0\cf2 {\listtext	7.	}Connect to your instance\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/EC2_GetStarted.html#ec2-connect-to-instance-linux"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 here}}.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400
\cf2 To connect to your instance using SSH you can start\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/AccessingInstancesLinux.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 here}}.\
Before you try to SSH make sure that your instance is running and that the checks have passed. This should involve typing something along the lines of\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 ssh -i ./me-key-pair-uswest2.pem\'a0ec2-user@YOUR_PUBLIC_DNS
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
Once you've connected via SSH, you can exit out of the shell by typing\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 exit
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl520\sa200

\fs48 \cf2 Securely copying files to the EC2 Instance with scp\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf2 To move files to your EC2 instance, we use the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 scp
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0command to securely copy information. We will need our\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 pem
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0file that we used before so make sure you know where that is located. The pattern for\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 scp
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0looks like this:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 scp -i PATH_TO_YOUR_PEM_FILE FILE_TO_MOVE\'a0USERNAME@PUBLIC_DNS
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
This command would move the file\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 move.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0from my current directory to the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 home
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0directory on my EC2 instance.\

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 scp -i ./me-key-pair-uswest2.pem move.txt\'a0ec2-user@ec2-54-213-7-226.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com:/
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl520\sa200

