\fs48 \cf2 cut\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf2 The\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 cut
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0command is very useful for separating or delimiting strings and characters. If you need to split apart text files or find certain characters,\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 cut
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0is the way to go. Let's see how it works with a few examples in a file called\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 :\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf2 \cb11 Java,James\
Ruby,Matz\
Lisp,John\
Bash,Brian\
Self,David\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 Here's an example using\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 cut
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0to grab the first 4 characters of each line (the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 -c
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0flag indicates that the numerical range coming after the flag is referencing characters, not bytes):\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 cut -c 1-4 languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf2 \cb11 Java\
Ruby\
Lisp\
Bash\
Self\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 Now let's grab the last names, but not by the number of characters. Instead, let's do this by delimiting (splitting) on the comma\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 cut -d, -f2 languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf2 \cb11 James\
Matz\
John\
Brian\
David\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 So what is the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 -f2
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 ?\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 -f
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0refers to each portion that has been split by the delimeter (
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 -d
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 ) flag. So if we just want the names we can do\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 cut -d, -f1 languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf2 \cb11 Java\
Ruby\
Lisp\
Bash\
Self\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 This is much better because if we had languages of different character lengths,\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 cut -c 1-4 languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0would not work!\
Next, try to use\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 cut
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0to print out just the authors. Then sort them and then return the first two authors!\
Here's one solution:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 cut -d, -f2 languages.txt | sort | head -n 2
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl520\sa200

\fs48 \cf2 sed\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf2 Sed, or Stream EDitor, is one of the\'a0
\i much
\i0 \'a0more complex terminal commands, so we will only be going over some simple uses cases. There are many, many things you can do with\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 sed
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 so try to follow these examples and push yourself to keep learning!\
Sed is commonly used for finding and replacing text, editing text in a file, and printing certain parts of a file (though it can to much more). Let's start by finding and replacing each comma in the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0file with a colon.\
Here's the command:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 sed 's/,/:/g' languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
Let's break this down:\

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 sed
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- the command\uc0\u8232 
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 s
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- substitute\uc0\u8232 
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 ,
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- our old value, a comma\uc0\u8232 
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 :
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- our new value\uc0\u8232 
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 g
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- globally, do this everywhere not just the first match\uc0\u8232 
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- the file we are working with\
Here's what the command should output:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf2 \cb11 Java:James\
Ruby:Matz\
Lisp:John\
Bash:Brian\
Self:David\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 Notice that if you\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 cat languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0after running the above\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 sed
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0command, the original file is unchanged. In order to edit the file, we need to use the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 i
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0flag to edit in place. But if you try running the command with the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 -i
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0flag you'll get an error about extra characters. Since we are also specifying additional arguments, we need to use the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 -e
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0flag as well.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 sed -ie 's/,/:/g' languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
If you run this command, and then\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 cat languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 , you should see that everything has been replaced!\
We are just scratching the surface with\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 sed
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 . If you want to learn more about it you can read\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.tutorialspoint.com/sed/sed_basic_syntax.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 this}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.panix.com/~elflord/unix/sed.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 this}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl520\sa200

\fs48 \cf2 awk\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf2 Similar to\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 sed
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 ,\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 awk
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0is an incredibly powerful text processing tool. In fact, AWK itself is actually a language that can pretty much do any kind of text manipulation you can think of. We will briefly cover\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 awk
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0and go over a few useful commands you can use with it.\
Let's start with the simple command\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 awk '\{print\}' languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 . This will simply print out the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0file. But what happens if we want to just print out a certain part of the file? We can also use\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 awk
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0as a delimiter using the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 -F
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0flag. Let's set\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 :
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0to be our delimiter and just print out the first portion delimited using\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 $1
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 awk -F ':' '\{print $1\}' languages.txt
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \
Let's look at another example, using the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 history
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0command. If you type this into the terminal, you should see a list of your recent commands. Let's use\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 awk
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0to get a history of just the names of the commands we've used, with no further details. When using\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 awk
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 , if the delimiter is an empty space we do not need the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 -F
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0flag. So if we want to find the commands we recently used we can type\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 history | awk '\{print $2\}'
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 .\
We can also use\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 awk
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0to print out rows and columns. For example, if you type\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 df -h
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0into the terminal you'll see a table withs some information on your hard drive (
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 df
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0is short for display free desk space). Let's pass the result of this command into\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 awk
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 :\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf2 \cb11 df -h | awk 'FNR == 2 \{print $4\}'\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 FNR refers to the record number which is usually a line number. Essentially we're telling\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 awk
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0to grab the item in the 2nd row and 4th column of the table, which in this case should be your available disk space.\
If you want to read more about\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 awk
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 , check out\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.tutorialspoint.com/awk/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 this}}\'a0tutorial.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl520\sa200

\fs48 \cf2 xargs\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf2 Sometimes you may want to execute the same command for multiple inputs. For instance, maybe you want to search multiple text files for a certain piece of text. This is a case where the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 xargs
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0command can be quite handy. Here are some example use cases for\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 xargs
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 ; each one runs command for a group of files instead of a single one.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 find . -name *.html | xargs grep "elie"
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- look for the text "elie" inside of every single\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 html
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0file in the current folder\

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 ls | xargs wc -l
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- counts the total amount of lines for each file in a folder\

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 find . -name "*" | xargs open
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- opens all of the files in the current folder.\

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 find . -name "*.css" | xargs open
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- opens all\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 css
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0files in the current folder\

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 find . -name "*.html | xargs rm
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- removes all files that end with\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 .html
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \

\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 ls | xargs -t -I \{\} mv \{\} \{\}.md
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- adds a markdown file extension to all files (the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 -I
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0flag replaces occurrences; the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 -t
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0flag causes the command that gets run for each input to be logged to the terminal before it is executed, which can be helpful for debugging).\
You can read more about\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 xargs
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/linux-unix-bsd-xargs-construct-argument-lists-utility/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 here}}\
