\fs48 \cf2 Shell Scripting\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf2 So far we have learned how to use terminal commands, but our commands are not dynamic. We know exactly what the filenames are or what we might be searching for. Our commands are also not reusable easily; if the filename changes, we have to write the whole command again. To reduce duplication and perform far more sophisticated commands in the terminal, we can write shell scripts using a language called bash. To get started, let's create a file called\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 first.sh
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0and inside place the following\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf2 \cb11 echo "Hello World"\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 Now if we try to run\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 ./first.sh
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0it will tell us\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 permission denied: ./first.sh
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 . So we need to make this program executable! Let's change permissions to\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 755
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0so that anyone can run this file:\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 chmod 755 first.sh
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 . Now we can run\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 ./first.sh
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 !\
Let's make a second script called\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 second.sh
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 . Inside of this file, type the following:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf2 \cb11 echo Hello $1\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 What do you think that\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 $1
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0represents? Let's first\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 chmod 755 second.sh
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0and then run\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 ./second.sh
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- we should just see "Hello". Now let's try\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 ./second.sh World
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0and we should see "Hello World"! What we just did was pass an argument to our script. Using arguments which start with\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 $1
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0and continue upward are how we can make more dynamic scripts.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl520\sa200

\fs48 \cf2 Your turn\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf2 Write a script called\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 sum.sh
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0which accepts two arguments and echoes the sum of the two numbers. You might need to do some research\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://stackoverflow.com/questions/6348902/how-can-i-add-numbers-in-a-bash-script"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 here}}.\
Here's a solution:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf2 \cb11 echo $(($1+$2))\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl520\sa200

\f0\fs48 \cf2 \cb1 More complex scripts\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf2 There is much more we can do with shell scripting, including conditional logic, if statements, and much more. But for now, let's try to write some handy scripts to help us with daily tasks. Very commonly we are searching for a process using\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 ps aux | grep "Something"
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 . Instead of typing that whole thing, we could make a script that does that for us and passes in an argument. Let's try that out with a script called\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 process.sh
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 . It might look something like this.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf2 \cb11 ps aux | grep $1\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 Now this is useful if we want to search for a process! If you would like to use the script frequently, you will want to make sure it is somewhere in your $PATH. You can also remove the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 .sh
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0extension if you are doing this.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl520\sa200

\fs48 \cf2 Vim\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf2 Vim is a terminal based text editor. It can be quite intimidating at first, but if you spend the time to learn how to use it, you can become an extremely efficient developer. To open up something in\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 vi
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 , simply type\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 vi NAME_OF_FILE
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 . Once you are in vim you can exit\'a0
\f2\b without
\f0\b0 \'a0saving by pressing\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 escape + : + q
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 . If that is not working press\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 escape
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0+\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 :
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0+\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 q!
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 . If you want to quit and save a file you can either press\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 shift + Z + Z
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0or\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 escape + : + w + q!
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 .\
When you first get into vim you will be in what is called\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 visual
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0mode. This means that your keyboard will be set for navigating and not for inserting characters; if you type letters and do not see anything being output, do not worry! To make insertions, press\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 i
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0to enter\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 insert
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0mode. Here you can make changes to files and type as you normally would. Just remember, if you want to quit out of a file you have to be in\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 visual
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0mode!\
You can get more practice by using\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 vimtutor
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0- just type\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf6 \cb7 vimtutor
\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb1 \'a0into your terminal and you can get started. Alternatively, if you want a more visual tutorial you can check out\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://vim-adventures.com/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 Vim Adventures}}.\
